{"title_page": "Padr\u00f3n peppers", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox cultivar\n| name = Padr\u00f3n\n| image = Pementos de Padron.jpg\n| image_caption  = Raw Padr\u00f3n peppers\n| origin = Galicia, Spain\n| species = ''[[Capsicum annuum]]''\n| module = {{Infobox pepper\n| embed = yes\n| heat     = \n| scoville = \n}}\n}}\n[[File:Pimientos de padron amb sal maldon.jpg|thumb|Fried Padr\u00f3n peppers]]\n\n'''Padr\u00f3n peppers''' ({{lang-gl|pementos de Padr\u00f3n}}) or '''Herb\u00f3n peppers''' are a variety of [[Capsicum|peppers]] (''Capsicum annuum'') from the municipality of [[Padr\u00f3n]] in the province of [[A Coru\u00f1a]], [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]], northwestern [[Spain]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Gourmetour: Food, Wine & Travel Quarterly Magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zz8sAQAAMAAJ|year=2000|publisher=INFE|page=89}}</ref> [[European Union]] law has protected the name ''Pimiento de Herb\u00f3n'' under the ''[[protected designation of origin]]'' since 2009 (PDO). These are small peppers about 2 inches (5&nbsp;cm) long, with a colour ranging from bright green to yellowish green, and occasionally red. Their peculiarity lies on the fact that, while their taste is usually mild, a minority (10-25%) are particularly hot. Whether a given pepper ends up being hot or mild depends on the amount of water and sunlight it receives during its growth, in addition to temperature. It's said that solely watering the soil of the plant is likely to produce milder pimentos, whilst watering the whole plant, leaves and stalks included, produces peppers of the spicier variety.<ref>Galician Grocer</ref>\n\nThe peppers are customarily fried in olive oil until the skin starts to blister and the pepper collapses. They are then served hot with the oil and a dusting of coarse salt, sometimes accompanied by chunks of bread, as [[tapas]].<ref name=\"Publishing2010\">{{cite book|author=DK Publishing|title=Back Roads Spain|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7LkM8Q7-MtUC&pg=PA34|date=15 February 2010|publisher=DK Publishing|isbn=978-0-7566-7181-5|pages=34\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Characteristics ==\nThese peppers are grown along the banks of the river [[Ulla (river)|Ulla]] and its tributary [[Sar (river)|Sar]], especially in the [[greenhouses]] of the municipality of [[Padr\u00f3n]], hence the name. This pepper is also currently grown in various places of southern [[Spain]], the [[United States]], [[Canada]] (primarily in the provinces of [[British Columbia]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.klippersorganics.com/|title=Welcome to Klippers Organics!|website=www.klippersorganics.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-14}}</ref>, [[Saskatchewan]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/KaleidoscopeVegetableGardens/|title=Kaleidoscope Vegetable Gardens|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-14}}</ref> and [[Ontario]]), [[Mexico]], and [[Morocco]]. They can also be grown in a warm place in the garden in the UK. The peppers are picked while their size is still small, starting as soon as mid-May. Traditionally, they were sold in the period going from late May until late October or, on occasion, even early November. However, the introduction of greenhouse plantations has made them available throughout the year.\n\nPadr\u00f3n peppers are small, with an elongated, conic shape. The taste is mild, but some exemplars can be quite hot, which property has given rise to the popular [[Galician language|Galician]] aphorism ''Os pementos de Padr\u00f3n, uns pican e outros non'' (\"Padr\u00f3n peppers, some are hot, some are not\").<ref name=\"Fedorchek2010\">{{cite book|author=Robert Fedorchek|title=The Translators|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7c5GP4DqDvUC&pg=PA258|date=21 September 2010|publisher=iUniverse|isbn=978-1-4502-4944-7|pages=258\u2013}}</ref> Typically, there is no way of determining whether a given pepper will be hot or mild, short of actually eating it, though some maintain that \nsmelling each cooked Padr\u00f3n for spice prior to eating is a good indicator.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Capsicum cultivars]]\n*[[Shishito]], a very similarly used pepper in Japan\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.pementodeherbon.com Pemento de HERB\u00d3N], Regulating Council of the Protected Designation of Origin.\n\n{{Capsicum cultivars}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Padron peppers}}\n[[Category:Capsicum cultivars]]\n[[Category:Chili peppers]]\n[[Category:Galician cuisine]]\n[[Category:Province of A Coru\u00f1a]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox cultivar\n| name = Padr\u00f3n\n| image = Pementos de Padron.jpg\n| image_caption  = Raw Padr\u00f3n peppers\n| origin = Galicia, Spain\n| species = ''[[Capsicum annuum]]''\n| module = {{Infobox pepper\n| embed = yes\n| heat     = \n| scoville = \n}}\n}}\n[[File:Pimientos de padron amb sal maldon.jpg|thumb|Fried Padr\u00f3n peppers]]\n\n'''Padr\u00f3n peppers''' ({{lang-gl|pementos de Padr\u00f3n}}) or '''Herb\u00f3n peppers''' are a variety of [[Capsicum|peppers]] (''Capsicum annuum'') from the municipality of [[Padr\u00f3n]] in the province of [[A Coru\u00f1a]], [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]], northwestern [[Spain]],<ref>{{cite book|title=Gourmetour: Food, Wine & Travel Quarterly Magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zz8sAQAAMAAJ|year=2000|publisher=INFE|page=89}}</ref> [[European Union]] law has protected the name ''Pimiento de Herb\u00f3n'' under the ''[[protected designation of origin]]'' since 2009 (PDO). These are small peppers about 2 inches (5&nbsp;cm) long, with a colour ranging from bright green to yellowish green, and occasionally red. Their peculiarity lies on the fact that, while their taste is usually mild, a minority (10-25%) are particularly hot. Whether a given pepper ends up being hot or mild depends on the amount of water and sunlight it receives during its growth, in addition to temperature. It's said that solely watering the soil of the plant is likely to produce milder pimentos, whilst watering the whole plant, leaves and stalks included, produces peppers of the spicier variety.<ref>Galician Grocer</ref>\n\nThe peppers are customarily fried in olive oil until the skin starts to blister and the pepper collapses. They are then served hot with the oil and a dusting of coarse salt, sometimes accompanied by chunks of bread, as [[tapas]].<ref name=\"Publishing2010\">{{cite book|author=DK Publishing|title=Back Roads Spain|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7LkM8Q7-MtUC&pg=PA34|date=15 February 2010|publisher=DK Publishing|isbn=978-0-7566-7181-5|pages=34\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Characteristics ==\nThese peppers are grown along the banks of the river [[Ulla (river)|Ulla]] and its tributary [[Sar (river)|Sar]], especially in the [[greenhouses]] of the municipality of [[Padr\u00f3n]], hence the name. This pepper is also currently grown in various places of southern [[Spain]], the [[United States]], [[Canada]] (primarily in the provinces of [[British Columbia]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.klippersorganics.com/|title=Welcome to Klippers Organics!|website=www.klippersorganics.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-14}}</ref>, [[Saskatchewan]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/KaleidoscopeVegetableGardens/|title=Kaleidoscope Vegetable Gardens|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-14}}</ref> and [[Ontario]]), [[Mexico]], and [[Morocco]]. They can also be grown in a warm place in the garden in the UK. The peppers are picked while their size is still small, starting as soon as mid-May. Traditionally, they were sold in the period going from late May until late October or, on occasion, even early November. However, the introduction of greenhouse plantations has made them available throughout the year.\n\nPadr\u00f3n peppers are small, with an elongated, conic shape. The taste is mild, but some exemplars can be quite hot, which property has given rise to the popular [[Galician language|Galician]] aphorism ''Os pementos de Padr\u00f3n, uns pican e outros non'' (\"Padr\u00f3n peppers, some are hot, some are not\").<ref name=\"Fedorchek2010\">{{cite book|author=Robert Fedorchek|title=The Translators|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7c5GP4DqDvUC&pg=PA258|date=21 September 2010|publisher=iUniverse|isbn=978-1-4502-4944-7|pages=258\u2013}}</ref> Typically, there is no way of determining whether a given pepper will be hot or mild, short of actually eating it, though some maintain that \nsmelling each cooked Padr\u00f3n for spice prior to eating is a good indicator.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Capsicum cultivars]]\n*[[Shishito]], a very similarly used pepper in Japan\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.pementodeherbon.com Pemento de HERB\u00d3N], Regulating Council of the Protected Designation of Origin.\n\n{{Capsicum cultivars}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Padron peppers}}\n[[Category:Capsicum cultivars]]\n[[Category:Chili peppers]]\n[[Category:Galician cuisine]]\n[[Category:Province of A Coru\u00f1a]]\n", "name_user": "Bernopedia", "label": "safe", "comment": "Grammar change", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Padr%C3%B3n_peppers"}
